{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17611681","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17611681"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:13:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:13:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16236"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16236","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16236"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.42,0,0.23,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8927"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74622"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8927","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8927"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16236"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60116"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5365"},{"type":"tags","id":"7662"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"8221"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21244"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21248"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74622","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74622"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EMedullary carcinoma of the breast is a rare subtype of breast cancer that has distinct histological features. It is important to recognise these features for accurate diagnosis and treatment planning.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the histological features of medullary carcinoma of the breast?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Spindle-shaped cells with collagen deposition","Large tumour cells with abundant cytoplasm and prominent nucleoli","Small, uniform cells with scant cytoplasm","Clusters of small cells with neuroendocrine features","Glandular structures with mucin production"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EMedullary carcinoma of the breast is characterised by \u003Cstrong\u003Elarge tumour cells with abundant cytoplasm and prominent nucleoli\u003C/strong\u003E. These cells often form sheets or syncytial patterns and are accompanied by a significant lymphoplasmacytic infiltrate. The tumour typically lacks glandular structures and has a pushing border.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESmall, uniform cells with scant cytoplasm\u003C/strong\u003E - This description is more typical of lobular carcinoma\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlandular structures with mucin production\u003C/strong\u003E - This is characteristic of mucinous carcinoma\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpindle-shaped cells with collagen deposition\u003C/strong\u003E - This is seen in metaplastic carcinoma\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClusters of small cells with neuroendocrine features\u003C/strong\u003E - This is typical of neuroendocrine carcinoma\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERecognising the histological features of medullary carcinoma is crucial for distinguishing it from other types of breast cancer.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Medullary carcinoma of the breast is characterised by large, high-grade tumour cells with abundant cytoplasm and prominent nucleoli.","The tumour often shows a syncytial growth pattern with poorly defined cell borders and a lymphoplasmacytic infiltrate.","Medullary carcinoma typically lacks glandular structures and has a pushing, rather than infiltrative, border."],"references":["Martinez SR, Beal SH, Canter RJ, Chen SL, Khatri VP, Bold RJ. Medullary carcinoma of the breast: a population-based perspective. Med Oncol. 2011 Sep;28(3):738-44. doi: 10.1007/s12032-010-9526-z. PMID: 20390465; PMCID: PMC4596814.","Limaiem F, Mlika M. Medullary Breast Carcinoma. 2023 Jan 1. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 31194432.","Kleer CG. Carcinoma of the breast with medullary-like features: diagnostic challenges and relationship with BRCA1 and EZH2 functions. Arch Pathol Lab Med. 2009 Nov;133(11):1822-5. doi: 10.5858/133.11.1822. PMID: 19886718; PMCID: PMC5058332.","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60116"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16236"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60116","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60116"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-25T22:25:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-25T22:57:07+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8927"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74622"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","nam